INSIGHTS
================================================================

── DEPARTMENT, CATEGORY & BRAND STRUCTURE ──────────────────────

  · Sweet Tooth is the largest department (12,513 SKUs, ~20% of
    catalog), yet it is the least discounted (11.43% avg).
  · Cold Drinks and Juices is the largest single category (7,496
    SKUs), followed by Bath and Body (6,841) and Chocolates (5,942).
  · NOICE leads brand listing count (1,567), ahead of legacy
    brands Amul (1,436) and Cadbury (1,089).
  · Plum and Minimalist — D2C beauty brands — appear in the top
    10 brands, signaling strong skincare catalog presence.
  · Product price is extremely right-skewed: most products are
    priced below ₹500, with a long tail reaching ₹47,000.


── DISCOUNT STRATEGY ───────────────────────────────────────────

  · Atta, Rice & Dal (22.02%) and Beauty & Cosmetics (21.63%)
    receive the highest average discounts — despite lower volumes.
  · Sweet Tooth (11.43%) and Cold Drinks & Juices (12.08%) are
    the least discounted departments despite dominating the catalog.
  · Insight: High-demand, impulse-purchase categories require
    less price incentive; staples and personal care need more.
  · The discount gap between the most and least discounted
    department is 10.59 percentage points.
  · Baby Care (19.95%) and Bakery & Biscuits (19.82%) sit just
    below the 20% mark — a near-uniform discount tier.

  Brand-level discount behavior (Top 10):
  · Supreme Harvest: highest consistent discount (~34% median)
  · NOICE: frequently discounted (~27% median); occasional 60–75%
  · Amul: near-zero median discount; selective outliers to ~70%
  · Paper Boat: almost no discount (~2% median); rare promotions
  · Minimalist and Plum: stable, consistent discounts (15–20%)
  · Cadbury and Milky Mist: mostly low discounts; sporadic promos
  · Insight: Discount is a brand-level strategy, not category-wide


── AVAILABILITY & STOCK ────────────────────────────────────────

  · Platform-wide stockout rate: 39.1% (24,905 of 63,670 items
    are out of stock).
  · Ice Creams and Frozen Desserts: 52.34% OOS — worst category;
    more than half of all listed SKUs are unavailable.
  · Cold Drinks & Juices (48.24%), Dairy, Bread and Eggs (45.96%),
    and Biscuits and Cakes (44.99%) follow closely.
  · All top 8 highest-OOS categories are food and beverage —
    indicating a systemic supply chain gap in food categories.
  · Sweet Tooth and Cold Drinks & Juices show near 1:1 in-stock
    to OOS ratios — severe for the two highest-volume departments.
  · Skincare (22.29%), Makeup (24.41%), and Baby Care (27.49%)
    are the best-stocked categories.
  · Personal Care and Beauty & Cosmetics maintain over 73% stock
    availability — the healthiest departments on the platform.


── PRICE vs DISCOUNT RELATIONSHIP ─────────────────────────────

  · Correlation between product_price and discount_in_percent
    = -0.003 (essentially zero).
  · Discount is entirely decoupled from product price — expensive
    products are not given higher discounts, and vice versa.
  · Scatter analysis confirms: products priced below ₹1,000 show
    the widest discount range (0%–80%); products above ₹2,000
    cluster near 0% discount across all top categories.
  · Insight: Discounting is a brand/category strategy, not a
    price-sensitivity response.


── PREMIUM vs MASS BRAND POSITIONING ──────────────────────────

  · Dyson is the highest average-priced brand (₹45,900 avg)
    with only 8% avg discount — brand value sustains demand.
  · HomeBasic is the highest discounted brand (83% avg discount)
    at ₹999 avg price — heavy promotion drives volume.
  · Calvin Klein (₹3,585), Olaplex (₹3,200), and Jean Paul
    Gaultier (₹2,793) lead premium pricing after Dyson.
  · Most brands cluster below ₹2,000 avg price, confirming
    Swiggy Instamart is primarily a mass-market grocery platform.
  · Premium brands compete on brand equity; mass-market brands
    compete aggressively through discounts.


── STORE & LOCATION ANALYSIS ───────────────────────────────────

  · Dataset covers 5 stores across 5 Bengaluru pin codes only —
    all locations in Karnataka, India.
  · Store-level avg price ranges from ₹264.95 (Begur, 560114)
    to ₹291.11 (Kumaraswamy Layout, 560111) — a ₹26 spread.
  · Pin code-level avg discount range: 16.04% to 16.40% — very
    narrow, suggesting uniform platform-wide pricing in Bengaluru.
  · Insight: Location-based price and discount variation is
    minimal; supply availability varies more than pricing across
    stores.

  Store x Category OOS highlights (from pivot):
  · Ice Creams OOS is consistently 49–58% across ALL 5 stores —
    confirms platform-wide supply failure, not store-specific.
  · Kanakapura Rd store (560070): highest OOS for Ice Creams
    (58.28%) and Cereals (51.95%).
  · Kumaraswamy Layout store (560111): relatively better stock
    across most categories — lowest OOS in Bath and Body (20.41%)
    and Makeup (14.83%).
  · Begur store (560114): most balanced availability overall.


── CORRELATION SUMMARY ─────────────────────────────────────────

  · item_selling_price vs product_price = 1.00 (identical columns)
    → One column is redundant; drop one for modeling/reporting.
  · item_mrp vs item_selling_price = 0.97 — prices track MRP closely.
  · discount_in_percent vs all price columns ≈ 0 — no relationship.
  · stock_count is independent of price, MRP, and discount (~-0.08).


================================================================
KEY TAKEAWAYS FOR SUBMISSION
================================================================

  1. Swiggy Instamart Bengaluru has a 39.1% platform-wide OOS
     rate — a critical supply chain problem concentrated in food.

  2. The highest-volume departments (Sweet Tooth, Cold Drinks)
     are the least discounted and most stocked out — demand
     exceeds supply without price incentives.

  3. Staple and personal care categories are discounted most
     aggressively, suggesting price-sensitive consumer targeting.

  4. Discount and price are completely independent (r = -0.003);
     discounting is brand/category driven, not price driven.

  5. Premium brands (Dyson, Calvin Klein) maintain low discounts;
     mass-market brands (HomeBasic, Supreme Harvest) lead on offers.

  6. All data originates from 5 Bengaluru stores — findings are
     city-specific and cannot be generalized nationally.

  7. item_selling_price and product_price are perfectly correlated
     (r = 1.00) and represent duplicate information in the dataset.

